```c#
var formatter = new Serilog.Sinks.SystemConsole.Output.OutputTemplateRenderer(ConsoleTheme.None, "{Message}", null);
var str = JsonSerializer.Serialize(new { a = 1, b = true }, new JsonSerializerOptions { WriteIndented = true }); // string with new line
var evt = DelegatingSink.GetLogEvent(l => l.Information("{@arg:l}", new { y = str }));
var sw = new StringWriter();
formatter.Format(evt, sw);
var res = sw.ToString();
Console.WriteLine(res);
```

outputs
```
{y="{\r\n  \"a\": 1,\r\n  \"b\": true\r\n}"}
```
(\r\n not expected)

Now let's change `new { y = str }` to just `str`:
```c#
var formatter = new Serilog.Sinks.SystemConsole.Output.OutputTemplateRenderer(ConsoleTheme.None, "{Message}", null);
var str = JsonSerializer.Serialize(new { a = 1, b = true }, new JsonSerializerOptions { WriteIndented = true }); // string with new line
var evt = DelegatingSink.GetLogEvent(l => l.Information("{@arg:l}", y = str));
var sw = new StringWriter();
formatter.Format(evt, sw);
var res = sw.ToString();
Console.WriteLine(res);
```

outputs
```
{
  "a": 1,
  "b": true
}
```
(no \r\n as expected)

The question is how can I archive `:l` format behavior for inner properties of complex objects?

